<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-314-808  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 314 808.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T unions balk on early-retirement plans.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (personnel management).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsPersonnel ManagementStrategic PlanningRetirementUnions.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ATandamp;T UNIONS BALK ON EARLY-RETIREMENT PLANS NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A., 1990MAR 28 (NB) -- ATandamp;T wants to cut its workforce by 6,000 through earlyretirement, but its two unions have broken off talks concerning thereductions, calling them unfair layoffs.andM;The two unions, the Communications Workers of America and the InternationalBrotherhood of Electrical Workers, wound up striking against NYNEX for twomonths last year over financial issues.andP;  They claim ATandamp;T is trying toincrease profits at the expense of employees and customers.andM;The job cuts were first announced last December as a way to compete againstMCI and Sprint, to which it has been steadily losing market share.andM;The talks are in recess, an ATandamp;T spokesman said, and no new talks arescheduled.andP;  &quot;That is not a hopeful sign,&quot; the spokesman added.andP;  &quot;Nonetheless,either side can resume negotiations at the drop of a hat.andP;  ATandamp;T believes itsoffer is fair.&quot; ATandamp;T has reduced its workforce by 92,000 since 1984.andP;  Thespokesman continued, &quot;We're hoping the early retirement package will obviatethe need to go to lay-offs.andP;  When people retire, others aren't laid off.&quot;andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900330/Press Contact: Burke Stinson, ATandamp;T, 201-221-2062)</TEXT></DOC>